Let \(f(x)=\tanh^{-1}(\cos x)\).  Then by the chain‐rule and \(\frac{d}{du}\tanh^{-1}u=\frac1{1-u^2}\) we have

\[
f'(x)
=\frac{d}{dx}\tanh^{-1}(\cos x)
=\frac{-\sin x}{1-\cos^2x}
=-\frac{\sin x}{\sin^2x}
=-\frac1{\sin x}
=-\csc x,
\]

valid for \(\cos x\in(-1,1)\) (so that \(\tanh^{-1}\) is defined) and \(\sin x\neq0\).
